      { type: "h1", text: "Appendix B\nThe Strategy Glossary" },
      { type: "p", text: "To actually change how a manufacturing company operates, the leadership team must first change how they speak. When a CEO forces their team to use these exact terms, it instantly elevates the boardroom conversation from low-level operational fire-fighting to high-level strategic design." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Activity System" },
      { type: "p", text: "A tightly integrated web of hundreds of daily operational choices (hiring, layout, software, tool crib management) that are perfectly tuned to support a specific competitive advantage. Because it is a complex system and not a single machine, it is mathematically impossible for a competitor to copy it quickly." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Capabilities" },
      { type: "p", text: "The specific operational \"muscles\" (equipment, human skill, proprietary knowledge, and supply chain leverage) a company must build to make their How to Win a reality." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Cost Leadership Advantage" },
      { type: "p", text: "A highly engineered business model where the actual internal cost to produce a part is structurally lower than anyone else in the market, usually achieved through extreme volume and specialization. (Note: This is completely different from simply offering a cheaper price and sacrificing your profit margin)." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Differentiation Advantage" },
      { type: "p", text: "A structural advantage achieved when a customer is willing to pay a premium because a company offers something highly specific (extreme speed, deep supply chain integration, proprietary metallurgy) that they cannot get anywhere else." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Laudable List" },
      { type: "p", text: "A collection of universally accepted \"good\" goals—such as better quality, faster delivery, and excellent customer service—masquerading as a strategy. Because every competitor claims to do these things, they provide zero competitive advantage." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Management Systems" },
      { type: "p", text: "The \"nervous system\" of a strategy. The specific KPIs, daily shop-floor meetings, software dashboards, and incentive structures required to enforce the company's Capabilities and protect its Trade-Offs." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Planning" },
      { type: "p", text: "The internal, controllable process of allocating resources to do what the company already does, but slightly better, faster, or cheaper (e.g., buying a machine, hiring a salesperson). Planning is mandatory for survival, but it is not strategy." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Straddling" },
      { type: "p", text: "The lethal operational mistake of trying to maintain a generic, high-volume business model while simultaneously bolting on a highly specialized, premium strategy under the same roof. The opposing cultures and metrics will destroy the factory's efficiency and brand value." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Strategy" },
      { type: "p", text: "An integrated set of difficult, external choices that positions a company on a specific playing field ( Where to Play ) with a structural, uncopyable advantage ( How to Win )." },
      { type: "h2", text: "The Dip" },
      { type: "p", text: "The terrifying, mathematical certainty that top-line revenue will temporarily drop when a company begins enforcing strategic trade-offs and firing bad, low-margin customers before the new premium pipeline fully converts." },
      { type: "h2", text: "The Lock & Load Error (Premature Sequencing)" },
      { type: "p", text: "The fatal mistake of choosing an attractive market arena ( Where to Play ) and committing capital to it before figuring out if the company actually possesses a unique, structural way to win there ( How to Win )." },
      { type: "h2", text: "The Opposite Test" },
      { type: "p", text: "The ultimate boardroom filter to determine if a stated goal is an actual strategy or just an operating imperative. If the opposite of the stated goal sounds stupid or like a recipe for bankruptcy, it is not a strategic choice." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Trade-Offs" },
      { type: "p", text: "The explicit, painful choices a company makes about what it will not do, who it will not serve, and what revenue it will reject. Trade-offs are the true source of a competitive moat because large competitors are financially unwilling to make the same sacrifices." },
      { type: "h2", text: "What Would Have to Be True? (WWHTBT)" },
      { type: "p", text: "The ultimate strategic diagnostic question. It replaces the demand for historical \"proof\" (which doesn't exist for new ideas) and forces leadership teams to identify the hidden, testable assumptions required for a new strategy to succeed." }
    ]
  }
];


